<h1>{t}Product Owner{/t}</h1>
<p>
 {t}The Product Owner represents the stakeholders.{/t}
 {t}He or she is the voice of the target audience, that is the Bible reader.{/t}
 {t}The Product Owner may also be a group of people in a committee.{/t}
</p>
<br>
<p>
 {t}He is accountable for ensuring that the team delivers accuracy and reliability to the Bible translation.{/t}
</p>
<br>
<p>
 {t}He defines items that focus on desired features.{/t}
 {t}He makes decisions as to whether to implement footnotes or leave them out.{/t}
 {t}In the same way, he defines other features, like headers, introductions, or decides to leave them out.{/t}
 {t}He decides about use or non-use of a dialect.{/t}
</p>
<br>
<p>
 {t}He sets the priorities for the work to be done.{/t}
 {t}He adds the items to the product backlog.{/t}
</p>
<br>
<p>
 {t}Scrum teams should have one Product Owner.{/t}
 {t}The Product Owner may be part of the Translation Team, but it is recommended that this role not be combined with that of the Scrum Master.{/t}
</p>
